				\begin{document}${{\mathcal I}^ +}$\end{document} could be compactified and included in the numerical grid. Rather than the explicit scheme used in CCM, the new version employs an implicit, second order in space and time, Crank-Nicholson evolution scheme. The code showed long-term stability and second-order convergence in vacuum tests based upon exact Weber-Wheeler waves [301] and Xanthopoulos’ rotating solution [307], and in tests of wave scattering by a string. The results show damped ringing of the string after an incoming Weber-Wheeler pulse has excited it and then scattered to \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
